{"title_page": "The One Day of the Year", "text_new": "{{Infobox play\n| name       = The One Day of the Year\n| image      =\n| image_size =\n| caption    =\n| writer     = [[Alan Seymour]]\n| characters =\n| setting    =\n| premiere   = 20 July 1960\n| place      = Adelaide\n| orig_lang  = English\n| subject    =\n| genre      =\n}}\n'''''The One Day of the Year''''' is an Australian play by [[Alan Seymour]] originally written in 1958 about [[Anzac Day]].\n\n==Plot==\nAlf\u2019s son Hughie and his girlfriend Jan plan to document Anzac Day for the university newspaper, focusing on the drinking on Anzac Day. For the first time in his life Hughie refuses to attend the dawn service with Alf. When he watches the march on television at home with his mother and Wacka, he is torn between outrage at the display and love for his father\n\n==Characters==\nAlf Cook,\nDot Cook,\nHughie Cook,\nWacka Dawson and\nJan Castle\n\n==Origins==\nThe play was inspired by an article in the [[University of Sydney]] newspaper ''[[Honi Soit]]'' criticising Anzac Day and Seymour's own observations of how ex-servicemen behaved on that day. The character of Alf was based on Seymour's brother in law.<ref>{{cite news | first = Richard | last = Jinman | title = Stirring struggle endures to this Day | date = 2003-04-02 | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/04/01/1048962752382.html | work = Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 2012-01-10}}</ref>\n\n==Productions==\nThe play was rejected by the Adelaide Festival of Arts Board of Governors in 1960, but made its debut on 20 July 1960 as an amateur production by the Adelaide Theatre Group. Jean Marshall, the Director, and those involved in the Adelaide production received death threats. The first professional season was in April 1961 at the [[Palace Theatre, Sydney|Palace Theatre]] in Sydney. It proved controversial and Seymour also received death threats however it was popular and there have been productions ever since. In 1961 Seymour travelled to London where the play was directed by [[Raymond Menmuir]] at the [[Theatre Royal Stratford East]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/one-day-of-the-year-that-changed-writer-alan-seymours-life-20150324-1m67qx.html|title=One Day of the Year that changed writer Alan Seymour's life|first=Marc|last=McEvoy|date=25 March 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n==1962 Australian television version==\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = The One Day of the Year\n| series       = [[The General Motors Hour]]\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 2\n| director     = [[Rod Kinnear]]\n| teleplay     = John Sumner\n| producer     =\n| photographer =\n| airdate      = 7 July 1962 (Sydney, Melbourne)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org.au/files/People/1962/May%201962029%20OPT.pdf|page=7|title=Television for 1962|website=GMH People|date=May 1962}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Age|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gcVVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yMUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7065%2C3474254|title=Australian Drama on Two Channels|date=26 April 1962|page=12}}</ref>\n| length       =\n| guests       =\n| prev         = [[Suspect (TV play)|Suspect]]\n| next         = [[Candida (TV play)|Candida]]\n}}\nThe play was adapted for Australian TV in June 1962. It was directed by [[Rod Kinnear]] and adapted by [[John Sumner (director)|John Sumner]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0382208/ ''The One Day of the Year''] at [[IMDb]]</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Controversial Play On ATN|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=25 June 1962|page=10}}</ref> Australian TV drama was relatively rare at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/60-australian-tv-plays-1950s-60s/|magazine=Filmink|title=60 Australian TV Plays of the 1950s & \u201860s|date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\n* [[Syd Conabere]] as Alf\n* Stewart Weller as Wacka\n* [[Dennis Miller]] as Hughie\n* Elaine Cusick as Jan Castle\n* [[Bunney Brooke]] as Dot Cook\n\n===Production===\nThe production was produced by GTV-9 in Melbourne after a 16 week run of the show in which 28,000 people saw the show. It was estimated 300,000 would see the television production.<ref{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=MDQ-9Oe3GGUC&dat=19620705&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|newspaper=The Age|title=Ten Times as Likely to See TV Version of Play|date=5 July 1962|page=8}}</ref>\n\nIt was the first of three plays of ''[[The General Motors Hour]]'' that year. The cast were all members of the Melbourne Union Theatre Repertory Company, which originally presented the play in Melbourne and toured three states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/event/77783|title=AusStage|website=www.ausstage.edu.au}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/event/106262|title=AusStage|website=www.ausstage.edu.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|title=Show Business|date=17 June 1962|page=84}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nThe TV critic for the ''Sydney Morning Herald'' said the shortened adaptation \"suffered much less than might have been expected in its transfer\" to television, saying it \"sometimes tended to focus more sharply the growing and bitter awareness of the increasing estrangement between an ill-educated, soured lift-driver and his university student son. On' the other hand, some scenes of richly meaningful theatrical impact missed badly.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The One Day-On Channel 7|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=9 July 1962|page=7}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Bulletin'' called it \"awful\".<ref>{{Citation\n  |\n  | title=The bulletin\n  | publication-date=1880\n  | publisher=John Haynes and J.F. Archibald\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-680306981\n  | accessdate=23 March 2019\n}} </ref>\n\nThe TV movie won Best Drama and Best Actor (for Syd Conabere) at the [[Logie Awards of 1963]].<ref>[http://www.tvweeklogieawards.com.au/logie-history/1960s/1963/ Logie Awards History]</ref>\n\n==1962 British television version==\nThe play was adapted for British TV in 1962 and produced by  [[James Ormerod]].\n\n===Cast===\n* [[Kenneth J. Warren|Kenneth Warren]] as Alf Cook\n* [[Reg Lye]] as Wacka\n* [[Madge Ryan]] as Dot Cook\n* [[George Roubicek]] as Hughie Cook\n* Georgina Ward as Jan Castle\n\n==Film adaptation==\nFilm rights were bought by Lou Edelmen Productions in 1970 but no film resulted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Loren, Mastroianni to Star|last=Martin|first= Betty|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=4 Mar 1970|page= g12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C251529 1960 play] at [[Austlit]]\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/7190713 1962 TV production] at [[Austlit]]\n{{Rod Kinnear}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:One Day of the Year, The}}\n[[Category:Australian plays]]\n[[Category:Australian television plays]]\n[[Category:1960 plays]]\n[[Category:English-language plays]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox play\n| name       = The One Day of the Year\n| image      =\n| image_size =\n| caption    =\n| writer     = [[Alan Seymour]]\n| characters =\n| setting    =\n| premiere   = 20 July 1960\n| place      = Adelaide\n| orig_lang  = English\n| subject    =\n| genre      =\n}}\n'''''The One Day of the Year''''' is an Australian play by [[Alan Seymour]] originally written in 1958 about [[Anzac Day]].\n\n==Plot==\nAlf\u2019s son Hughie and his girlfriend Jan plan to document Anzac Day for the university newspaper, focusing on the drinking on Anzac Day. For the first time in his life Hughie refuses to attend the dawn service with Alf. When he watches the march on television at home with his mother and Wacka, he is torn between outrage at the display and love for his father\n\n==Characters==\nAlf Cook,\nDot Cook,\nHughie Cook,\nWacka Dawson and\nJan Castle\n\n==Origins==\nThe play was inspired by an article in the [[University of Sydney]] newspaper ''[[Honi Soit]]'' criticising Anzac Day and Seymour's own observations of how ex-servicemen behaved on that day. The character of Alf was based on Seymour's brother in law.<ref>{{cite news | first = Richard | last = Jinman | title = Stirring struggle endures to this Day | date = 2003-04-02 | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/04/01/1048962752382.html | work = Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 2012-01-10}}</ref>\n\n==Productions==\nThe play was rejected by the Adelaide Festival of Arts Board of Governors in 1960, but made its debut on 20 July 1960 as an amateur production by the Adelaide Theatre Group. Jean Marshall, the Director, and those involved in the Adelaide production received death threats. The first professional season was in April 1961 at the [[Palace Theatre, Sydney|Palace Theatre]] in Sydney. It proved controversial and Seymour also received death threats however it was popular and there have been productions ever since. In 1961 Seymour travelled to London where the play was directed by [[Raymond Menmuir]] at the [[Theatre Royal Stratford East]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/one-day-of-the-year-that-changed-writer-alan-seymours-life-20150324-1m67qx.html|title=One Day of the Year that changed writer Alan Seymour's life|first=Marc|last=McEvoy|date=25 March 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n==1962 Australian television version==\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = The One Day of the Year\n| series       = [[The General Motors Hour]]\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 2\n| director     = [[Rod Kinnear]]\n| teleplay     = John Sumner\n| producer     =\n| photographer =\n| airdate      = 7 July 1962 (Sydney, Melbourne)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org.au/files/People/1962/May%201962029%20OPT.pdf|page=7|title=Television for 1962|website=GMH People|date=May 1962}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Age|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gcVVAAAAIBAJ&sji