==Reception===\nThe TV critic for the ''Sydney Morning Herald'' said the shortened adaptation \"suffered much less than might have been expected in its transfer\" to television, saying it \"sometimes tended to focus more sharply the growing and bitter awareness of the increasing estrangement between an ill-educated, soured lift-driver and his university student son. On' the other hand, some scenes of richly meaningful theatrical impact missed badly.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The One Day-On Channel 7|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=9 July 1962|page=7}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Bulletin'' called it \"awful\".<ref>{{Citation\n  |\n  | title=The bulletin\n  | publication-date=1880\n  | publisher=John Haynes and J.F. Archibald\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-680306981\n  | accessdate=23 March 2019\n}} </ref>\n\nThe TV movie won Best Drama and Best Actor (for Syd Conabere) at the [[Logie Awards of 1963]].<ref>[http://www.tvweeklogieawards.com.au/logie-history/1960s/1963/ Logie Awards History]</ref>\n\n==1962 British television version==\nThe play was adapted for British TV in 1962 and produced by  [[James Ormerod]].\n\n===Cast===\n* [[Kenneth J. Warren|Kenneth Warren]] as Alf Cook\n* [[Reg Lye]] as Wacka\n* [[Madge Ryan]] as Dot Cook\n* [[George Roubicek]] as Hughie Cook\n* Georgina Ward as Jan Castle\n\n==Film adaptation==\nFilm rights were bought by Lou Edelmen Productions in 1970 but no film resulted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Loren, Mastroianni to Star|last=Martin|first= Betty|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=4 Mar 1970|page= g12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C251529 1960 play] at [[Austlit]]\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/7190713 1962 TV production] at [[Austlit]]\n{{Rod Kinnear}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:One Day of the Year, The}}\n[[Category:Australian plays]]\n[[Category:Australian television plays]]\n[[Category:1960 plays]]\n[[Category:English-language plays]]\n